    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix deadlock in thread pool due to inconsistent lock ordering after condwait\n\n### Summary\nThere is a deadlock caused by inconsistent lock acquisition ordering downstream of function condwait in common/utils/threadPool/thread-pool.c. The issue occurs when a thread pool worker tries to push a result back to the same FIFO it's consuming from, causing a double-lock attempt on the same mutex.\n\nSpecifically, in the `one_thread` function, when processing an element with a response FIFO that is the same as the incoming FIFO, the code attempts to lock `tp->incomingFifo.lockF` twice - once explicitly in `one_thread` and again implicitly in `pushNotifiedFIFO`. This causes a deadlock since normal pthread mutexes are not recursive by default.\n\nThe fix adds a check to avoid double-locking when the response FIFO is the same as the incoming FIFO, using the thread-unsafe version of the push function in that specific case.\n\n### Changes\n- `common/utils/threadPool/thread-pool.c`: Added check to avoid double-locking when response FIFO equals incoming FIFO\n- `common/utils/threadPool/thread-pool.h`: Improved condwait macro safety with do-while loop wrapper\n\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Configure a thread pool with elements that have their response FIFO set to the same FIFO they're being processed from\n2. Start the thread pool processing\n3. Observe deadlock when threads attempt to push results back to the same FIFO\n\nSymptoms include threads hanging indefinitely during NG setup or other thread pool operations, with all worker threads stuck in mutex acquisition.\n"
}